Backport of upstream commit 58f9a1d166dcb0c274807d4423522d205b0c35ea
("Avoid overflow by not adding extents together (#9520)") for Pillow 11.2.1.

CVE-2026-42311 / GHSA-pwv6-vv43-88gr (regression of CVE-2026-25990).

The PSD plugin (and any decoder/encoder fed crafted tile extents) could trigger
an integer overflow in the bounds check `xsize + xoff > im->xsize`, bypassing
validation and producing an out-of-bounds write in the C decoder/encoder.

Fix: validate the raw extents (x0, y0, x1, y1) against the image bounds BEFORE
performing any subtraction, in src/PIL/ImageFile.py PyCodec.setimage(),
src/decode.c _setimage() and src/encode.c _setimage().

This backport adapts the upstream fix to the 11.2.1 surrounding code:
  * 11.2.1 PyCodec keeps the existing `if x0 == 0 and x1 == 0` branch, so the
    early raw-extent check is added inside the `else` branch only (preserving the
    (0, 0, 0, 0) full-image sentinel used by setimage(im) without extents).
  * 11.2.1 decode.c / encode.c lack the upstream `xoff < 0 / yoff < 0` guards,
    so we keep the existing trailing post-subtraction check intact and add a
    new pre-subtraction guard inside the non-sentinel else branch only.

Skipped from upstream diff (require GIT binary patch support which `patch -p1`
cannot consume; the underlying security fix in the source files above is
complete and self-sufficient without these test additions):
  * Tests/images/psd-oob-write-overflow.psd — 496-byte PSD fixture.
  * Tests/test_file_psd.py — adds test_bounds_crash_overflow which depends on
    that fixture.
  * Tests/test_imagefile.py — pure refactor (consolidates test_negsize /
    test_oversize into a parametrized test_extents). 11.2.1 already has
    equivalent non-parametrized coverage; refactor would only churn context
    without adding security validation.

